        I. Overview of the Network Operations PAPER Ticketing System

           A. Purpose

              The ticket program is a method of tracking BT TYMNET
              network anomalies from the time they are reported 
              until their resolution.

              The system includes an archive database in order to
              provide and track historical information on a particular
              problem/trouble/anomaly/project/preventive maintenance.

              It allows multiple users and service groups to access
              and interact with a uniform format for the purpose of
              tracking network issues.

           B. History

              The ticket system originated at NSSC, the Network
              Systems Support Center which monitors and maintains
              the private and subnetworks of BT Tymnet.
                
              The name of the ticketing system is PAPER.
              Pre-1984, network problems that were documented
              by the Network Systems Support Center (NSSC)
              were written on paper forms called tickets. 
              All the steps that were taken to resolve a
              problem were written on the form.  When the
              issue was resolved, the tickets were filed
              for possible future reference.
              Don Murtaugh; then manager of Network Operations
              wrote a program to enable the technicians to
              utilize a relational database on a PDP10
              instead of writing paper tickets. 
                                                                  
                                                                   
              Used originally by only a few  technicians that
              comprised NSSC,  PAPER has evolved into a worldwide
              ticketing system utilizing a relational database.



              


                                                                            







           C. Who Uses the Ticket System?

              PAPER originally was used only by NSSC, but even-
              tually it became a ticketing system for all U.S. 
              Network Operations groups. The Field Engineering
              organization was later given ability to insert
              statuses, including the U.S. Novadyne Computer
              Systems, Inc.   After a time, communications
              specialists, project managers, and eventually, ATT
              management, and customers were validated to view 
              and update tickets.  The list of valid users was
              then expanded to include Software Technical Support
              (STS), National Technical Support(NTS), National
              Technical Development(NTD), Project Implementation
              (PI), and finally, International Operations Groups, 
              and Support Personnel.   

              PAPER is now a worldwide ticketing system.  The status
              of users varies with the highest status  going to a
              'control group'.  A control group is an operations
              organization that can open and close tickets in addition
              to statusing and transferring tickets between refer groups.
              The user of a non-control group has the restriction of not
              opening or closing tickets.  


           D. Ticket Structure and Types

              A PAPER ticket consists of:  

                1. Header - which contains three columns of
                   information about the particular aspect of the
                   network that the ticket is referencing. (The
                   header is covered in full in section II.)
                   Some of the information in the header is entered
                   at the time a ticket is opened.  Some header
                   information is kept in a relational database. The
                   relational database will add the information to
                   the header of the ticket each time a new ticket is
                   opened on that particular network aspect.

                   Example:  The first time a ticket is opened
                             on host 123 of slot 1 of Node 11430 the
                             technician will be prompted to enter the
                             name of a contact at the node site.  Every
                             time thereafter that a ticket is opened on
                             host 123 or node 11430 the site contact
                             will automatically appear in the ticket 
                             header.


                                                                            






                2. Problem Description - appears just below the
                   ticket header and consists of a maximum of 10
                   lines of a brief description of the anomaly 
                   and any diagnostics or suggestions toward
                   resolution.

                3. Each  status consists of  up to 4 lines of
                   information in the steps toward resolution. A
                   status also contains information automatically
                   entered by the program such as,  the control 
                   group, the initials of the person entering the
                   status, the date, GMT time.

                4. PAPER recognizes 3 types of tickets in the following
                   categories:

                   Node    Host    Circuit

           E. Problems with the PAPER Ticket System

              Report any problems with the PAPER program to the
              control group handling the ticket.  The control 
              group will resolve the problem or refer it to 
              Network Control for resolution.

           F. Caution

              At NO TIME should a username or password appear
              any place in a ticket!

                   

          

 




                                                                             





