    I. SOFTWARE VERSION

       1. Indicates the current version of code running in the 
          node or slot at the time of the problem.

       2. The accuracy of this field is important at all times
          but it is critical when escalating a ticket to STS.

       3. Obtain the current version from the command file of
          the slot or node.


    J. SOFTWARE DISTRICT

       1. The office/district of the CS (Communications Specialist)
          that is assigned to the particular network/account.

       2. Please refer to Appendix C.



    K. PRIMARY

       1. Whether the outage is primary to the customer or not.
          NOT USED.

    L. OPEN BY

       1. Technician's initials are entered here -- the three 
          characters which were input when logging into PAPER.


    M. ZONE

       1. 1,2,3,or 4 depending on the distance from the site
          to the nearest Field Service office.

          1 = ONSITE
          2 = 0 - 50 MILES
          3 = 51 - 150 MILES
          4 = GREATER THAN 150 MILES


                                                                            







    N. SEVERITY

       1. Severity is 1,2,3,4, which reflects the severity level 
          of the problem; to be determined by the guidelines
          which can be found in Appendix D.
            
       2. The severity will determine when the problem will be
          escalated and how often the ticket will have to be
          updated (statused).

       3. Once the 'time up' or RESOLVE TIME (see 'W' this section)
          has been set, it is not necessary to change the severity.
          For example, if a node crashes and is reloaded but a 
          hardware dispatch to run diagnostics is desired the resolve
          time will be set up, but the severity of the ticket still
          remains a 1.

    O. STATE

       1. The state of the ticket will be:

          OPEN
          MONITOR
          TRACK
          CLOSED

          A. OPEN    - The ticket is in an active state.  
                                
          B. MONITOR - The problem/outage has been resolved but
                       there is a need to document a recurrence 
                       without opening a new ticket.

          C. TRACK   - When a ticket is being used for documentation;
                       activity is not expected.  Also for
                       documentation of future dispatches or releases.
                       MTTR* report is not affected.
                       *(Mean Time To Repair)

          D. CLOSED  - Ticket is inactivated and ready to be sent
                       to the archive database. Anomaly is resolved
                       and verified.






                   
     
    P. CONTROL GROUP

       1. The group that has opened the ticket will appear here.
          It is this group's responsibility to track the problem
          through resolution and close with the person/group
          that appears in the 'Reported By' field.
           
       2. The control group's are: NCS, NSSC, VANCF, or NETCON, but
          it can also be an International Group or a Customer
          if they have been given status to open tickets.

    Q. REFERRED TO

       1. Also known as the "ATTENTION GROUP" or the "Support
          Area".
         
       2. This field indicates who is to be currently working
          on the trouble.  

       3. These fields can be found in APPENDIX C with an 
          explanation of each abbreviation. 
            
          Example: The field engineer in New York might be
          dispatching on a trouble ticket.  The "Referred To"
          would read 'EFONY' which stands for Eastern Field 
          Operations New York.



     R. MGMT ESCAL  - (Management Escalation)

        1. Indicates if the ticket has been escalated.

        2. H1 would indicate no escalation within hardware.
           H2 would indicate an escalation to first level manager
           in hardware.
           S1 is the escalation field for software
           T1 is the escalation field for TELCO (telephone Company)

     S. TECH ESCAL  - (Technical Escalation)

        1. Defaults to NO.

        2. If a ticket is escalated to STS (Software Technical 
           Support) or NTS ( National Technical Support), the 
           field will become a YES and remain YES even after
           the ticket is referred to another group.





     T. DE-ESCAL CODE

        1. Defaults to 0

        2. If a ticket is de-escalated, the technician is prompted
           for a de-escalation code which will appear in this field
           either while a ticket is open or after it is closed.
        
     U. DEFER

        1. If there is not to be any action taken on a ticket
           (that is open with resolve time not set),  the ticket
           must be deferred to prevent the  accumulation of 
           elapsed time on the Mean Time To Repair.

        2. The field appears as #/#.

           The first number is the amount of time that the
           ticket is currently deferred in number of hours.

           The second number is the amount of cumulative 
           deferred number of hours. 

        3. See Appendix E for a list of instances in which
           you can defer a ticket.


     V. OPEN
        
        1. The date the ticket was opened.

        2. The time the ticket was opened in GMT time.

     W. RESLV - (Resolved)

        1. The date and time the problem was resolved or when
           service was restored. The outage time for the ticket
           is stopped at the time entered in this field.
            
        2. The service may be restored and the ticket can remain
           open. 

           Example:  Service is restored but diagnostics
           are scheduled for the node. If service is restored the
           resolve time should be set.

           When service is believed to be restored, but a period of
           time must pass before the customer can test and verify,
           set the resolve time to when the current restoration
           activity was completed.  When the customer can test (often
           the next morning) and they find restoration not complete,
           simply re-open the ticket as explained in section VIII C.







     X. CLOSE

        1. The date and time the ticket was actually closed.

     Y. ELAPS  - (Elapsed Time)

        1. The amount of time that has elapsed before a resolution
           has been found or service has been restored.
            
        2. The elapsed time stops incrementing when the resolve
           time is set up or the ticket is deferred.
           See Field W.

        3. Time shown in hours and tenths of hours.

     Z. CLSCD - (Closed)

        1. After a ticket is closed, the reason that it was closed
           will be indicated here using one of 10 different
           closeout codes.

        2. The technician is prompted for a closeout code when 
           closing a ticket.
               
           Section XI, provides a detailed discussion of closing
           tickets and the use of closeout codes.

     a. CUSTOMER

        1. This is the name of the customer or network.

        2. In the case of Private network customers, this field 
           will be the same as the NETWORK field - letter A.

        3. For Public Network, the NETWORK field will indicate 
           TYMNET but CUSTOMER will be the specific company with 
           the problem.
 
     b. CONTACT

        1. The name of the person or group at the actual site where 
           the node is located.  In the case of an internodal link 
           it is the contact at the low node number.

     c. CPHONE

        1. The telephone number of the above contact at the site.








     d. LOCALE

        1. The location of the node involved.

        2. This will be the low numbered node in the event of an
           internodal link involving two nodes.

     e. RPTD BY - (Reported By)

        1. The person who is reporting the problem.

        2. This may be the customer who called in the trouble,
           a customer help desk, or a monitoring group such as
           Network Control who has detected the trouble remotely.

        3. This person or group must give the okay that service
           has been restored or problem resolved before ticket
           is closed.

     f. RPHONE

        1. Phone number of the person or group that reported
           the problem.

     g. PLAN #
        
        1. The maintenance contract code indicating the time
           period the customer has contracted for maintenance.
            
        2. For maintenance plan codes and a complete explanation
           see Appendix F.

     h. SITE HR

        1. The hours that the site is open and available for 
           maintenance dispatch or assistance in troubleshooting.

        2. Site hours should be entered in GMT time.

     i. COM SPEC - (Communication Specialist) 

        1. The name of the Communications Specialist assigned to 
           the particular account is entered here.








     j. CKT #

        1. If the problem reported is a problem with a data
           communications line, the identifying circuit number
           is entered here. 

        2. Circuit number is a combination of letters and numbers 
           up to 20 digits.

        3. If the trouble ticket does not pertain to a circuit
           this field should be blank. Enter a carriage return at
           the prompt.

     k. TELCO #

        1. Pertaining to circuit number above ('j'), the trouble 
           number of the telephone company responsible for the 
           line/circuit is entered here.

     l. REF.TKT#

        1. Some customer operation groups also have a ticketing 
           system and request referencing their own ticket in 
           Tymnet's ticket.  If they do request this, enter their 
           ticket number here.

     m. BILL/T40

        1. BILL stands for Billable Service Call.
               
        2. If the needed maintenance is not covered by
           the customer's maintenance agreement, a YES should
           be entered here.
            
        3. The default is NO.

        4. T40 is whether customer is a TOP 40 customer of BT TYMNET.
           Private Network customers should always have this set to
           YES.
           



                                                                             





    

