        VII. DEFERMENTS

             A. Deferring a ticket means the technician is stopping
                the 'clock from ticking' on the repair time of the
                ticket.
                This means ---
                    1. If a ticket is opened on a trouble/problem and
                       the time of resolution is not set up, a timer
                       is logging the time it will take to repair the
                       problem.  This information is used to calculate
                       the Mean Time To Repair (MTTR).  MTTR is an
                       indication to operations groups and customers
                       as to how quickly anomalies are being resolved
                       or repaired.

                    2. Once the RESOLVE time is set in the ticket header,
                       the repair time clock will stop.

                    3. If there is an uncontrollable reason preventing 
                       maintenance or repair, the repair time clock needs
                       to be stopped temporarily.

                    4. The repair time clock is stopped by deferring the
                       ticket.

             B. Reasons for Deferment

                1. No access to the customer site.

                2. Customer has requested the repair be delayed.

                3. Outside of customer's principle maintenance
                   period.
                   See - Appendix F and Section V. of this 
                   document for more information on billing and
                   maintenance periods.

             C. Deferring a ticket

                1. There are two commands to defer a ticket.
        
                   a. 'D'
                   b. '8' after issuing an 'S'



                                                                            




                      'D'
                      Will prompt for a ticket number.
                      Then give a three choice menu:
 
                           1 = REDUCE DEFERMENT (ENTER NEGATIVE TIME)
                           2 = ZERO OUT DEFERMENT
                           3 = DEFER TICKET ACTION

                      Choose one of the above, and, if appropriate, the
                      program will prompt to enter the number of hours.
                    
                      Note: The maxium hours allowed for a single deferment
                            is 144 hours.  If additional deferment is
                            needed, repeat the process.

                      Typing an 'S' and then choosing #8 from the menu 
                      will accomplish the same thing as a D, but will
                      allow the technician to first enter a ticket status. 

                2. The ticket header 'DEFER' will reflect the number
                   of hours the ticket is currently deferred and the
                   number of total hours the ticket has been deferred.
                 - See Section III U.

                   Additionally, The ELAPS:  Elapsed time is calculated
                   from the time the ticket is opened.  If a ticket
                   is deferred, the effect on elapsed time will not
                   be affected while ticket is open.  Deferral times
                   are used to determine elapsed time at the time a 
                   ticket is closed.


