         X. MONITOR
    
            A. The Use of Monitor

   
               1. The monitor state can be used for up to 24 hours to
                  ensure stability of a network component prior to closing
                  a ticket.  At the end of the designated monitor period
                  (24 hour maxium), the trouble must be closed or reopened.
                  The monitor state should be used very sparingly.  In
                  most cases, when an outage has been resolved and verified,
                  the ticket should be closed.  An example of the use of
                  monitor would be to verify the "fix" (stability), of a
                  chronic problem such as intermittent errors on a circuit. 

            B. Placing a ticket on monitor:

               Type an 'S' from the menu choices use # 2. Type in an 
               informational status if desired. The time entered 
               automatically sets the resolve or time up.




                                                                            







         XI. CLOSING A TICKET
           
             A. WHEN TO CLOSE A TICKET
        
                1. There are 4 types of tickets to close:

                   a. Tickets reported by someone other than a Network
                      Technician.

                      Reported tickets have been opened at the request of
                      a customer, CS or Project manager. Such tickets should 
                      be closed with the person reporting the problem by 
                      calling and confirming the problem is resolved.  This 
                      person's name should always appear in the ticket header
                      under RPTD BY. The phone number to reach this person 
                      should appear in the ticket header under RPHONE (See 
                      also Section II)

                   b. Tickets reported by ontyme from a CS or
                      escalation group for escalation purposes to STS.

                      This type of ticket will generally be brought
                      to the operation groups attention by changing the
                      REFERRED GROUP in the ticket header.  The
                      ticket will then show up when a technician 
                      does a 'K' command (See also Section IX).
                      If at that time the CS, etc has statused the
                      ticket that a resolution has been reached and
                      the ticket can be closed, you can do so without
                      a phone call.

                   c. Tickets opened by an Operations Group. 
                     
                      This will occur when an anomaly is recorded 
                      through the various monitoring processes.
                      In these types of tickets, when the 
                      technician is satisfied that the problem is 
                      resolved, the ticket can be closed with
                      no phone call. *Exception: When there
                      have been call backs added to the ticket.
                      These people need to be called first.



                                                                            




                   d. A ticket opened on a problem which is now
                      resolved, but customer has requested a 
                      monitoring period.         


                2. In summary: close a ticket when the problem is 
                   confirmed resolved. Close a ticket with the 
                   concurrence of the reporting person or after an 
                   agreed monitoring period.


