      XII. REOPENING TICKETS

              A. The purpose of the ticket system is to record
                 problem occurrences.  Every time a problem occurs 
                 there should be a ticket to track it. Therefore, some
                 controls have been built into the PAPER program:

                 1. If the ticket has been closed for more than 24
                    hours the program will not allow it to be reopened.

                 2. If the 'resolve time' has been set up more
                    than 24 hours, a ticket cannot be reopened.  

                    (a) In this case, a technician would try to zero out
                        the resolve time if the problem reoccurred before
                        the ticket was closed.

                        Example:  A node crashes;  a dispatch takes place.
                                  A hardware fix is accomplished and service
                                  is restored. Ticket is statused.
                                  'Time up' is set (Resolve Time). While 
                                  verifying that everthing is O.K., the  
                                  node crashes again.  The ticket would then 
                                  be reopened to set the resolve time to zero
                                  since the service is gone. 
                                  This can be accomplished as long as the
                                  ticket had not remained open for 24 hours
                                  after the time up was set.

              B. Option #4 of the 'S' command will reopen a ticket
                 after it has been closed.

                        










